5000|$|The {{examination}} {{of whether the}} requirements for the accordance of a filing date [...] and other formal requirements are satisfied is {{carried out by the}} EPO, in accordance with [...] If a date of filing cannot be accorded, the application is not dealt with as a <b>European</b> <b>patent</b> <b>application.</b> If the <b>European</b> <b>patent</b> <b>application</b> has been accorded a date of filing, but if there are other formal deficiencies, the applicant is offered an opportunity to correct these deficiencies. If the deficiencies are not corrected, the <b>European</b> <b>patent</b> <b>application</b> is refused, unless a different legal consequence applies.|$|E
5000|$|As another example, a <b>European</b> <b>patent</b> <b>application</b> {{consists}} of [...] "a {{request for the}} grant of a European patent, {{a description of the}} invention, one or more claims, any drawings referred to in the description or claims, and an abstract." [...] specifies what the description of a <b>European</b> <b>patent</b> <b>application</b> should contain in more details.|$|E
5000|$|Under the EPC 1973, {{in order}} to {{preclude}} double patenting, the prior art effect of a first <b>European</b> <b>patent</b> <b>application</b> (a so-called [...] "conflicting patent application") filed before the filing date of a second <b>European</b> <b>patent</b> <b>application,</b> but published after said filing date, on the second application {{is limited to the}} designated states in common.|$|E
